website_summaries.verdict: Cost-effective choice, especially when buying in bulk. Easy calibration with new boxes so readings aren’t delayed. Great option if brand name isn’t covered by insurance.
pros: Affordable off-brand option for OneTouch strips so you can test more often
No need to worry about limiting your readings based on cost
In side by side comparison to brand name strips, consistently perform well and deliver accurate readings
cons: Some reports of inconsistent readings and error messages

customer_reviews.title: Very disappointing
customer_reviews.text: I found this product on Amazon which is much cheaper than the one I bought in Walgreens. But it didn’t work with the meter at all after I have tried seven stripes! Really disappointed. Please see the video I upload.
customer_reviews.author: Pam

customer_reviews.title: Not accurate!
customer_reviews.text: These glucose strips are totally inaccurate. Their measure of blood sugar, when compared with brand name strips, was always 10% to 25% lower. The higher the blood sugar, the larger the discrepancy. This could be dangerous if your blood sugar is very high! I returned the remainder of strips.
customer_reviews.author: E. Gaines

customer_reviews.title: Make sure you set the code in your meter. Great price.
customer_reviews.text: The price is great. They work good, you just need to set the code that is printed on the bottles. The strips were delived in a couple of days. The people that wrote negative reviews probably don't know how to follow instructions. Save your money and buy a great product that works. The drug companies that market the name brands are ripping us all off.
customer_reviews.author: kmuehter

customer_reviews.title: Excellent accuracy!
customer_reviews.text: HIghly accurate when compared to the One Touch strips, side-by-side with blood from same finger prick. No clue why US insurance companies don't just cover these strips.......cost to make them nowadays is extremely cheap. I highly recommend these. Shouldn't have to pay more than 27 - 30 bucks for 200 strips (many sellers, with many options on Amzn). I'm not sure about trying to use them in a One Touch mini (as I use) that was manufactured in/after 2016. (I see 1-2 other reviewers said something about that -- not sure of accuracy of that info at all).
customer_reviews.author: Mike W.

customer_reviews.title: Excellent value and readings track with A1C
customer_reviews.text: So far, so good with these test strips. Out of 200, only two or three were defective. Compared to the brand-name versions or the strips available through the FSA-approved store, these are a great value!
customer_reviews.author: secyatlaw

customer_reviews.title: I use these with my OneTouch Ultra meter and I ...
customer_reviews.text: I use these with my OneTouch Ultra meter and I have tested them side-by-side with the official OneTouch strips. There may be a 1-2 point difference at most on the reading, but that is the same as using 2 of the official strips right after each other as well. Just remember to check the code number on each order as they will not always be the same, and using the wrong code will provide inaccurate readings.
customer_reviews.author: JP Nunemaker

customer_reviews.title: Good Price, But Perhaps Worthless for the Pre Diabetic
customer_reviews.text: Tired of paying high prices for OEM strips, I tried these. At first I gave them 3 stars due to inconsistent readings. I have dropped that to 2 stars after getting readings of 105, 118, 127, and 133 this morning. For a pre-diabetic, this range makes the strips nearly worthless. I am going back to the more expensive brand.
customer_reviews.author: Evaluator

customer_reviews.title: their price is dramatically less than the pharmacy price.
customer_reviews.text: the reasonable price allows me to test my blood sugar level 4 times per day. I'm 80 years old and have been a type 2 diabetic for 30 years. Along with diet, exercise and weight control I'm nearly at the prediabetes level. I've been told, that if I was a bit younger, I could of reversed the T2D and became normal again. When I was first diagnosed I was told that it was not reversible
customer_reviews.author: patrick j. lynch

customer_reviews.title: Don't buy
customer_reviews.text: I opted to ignore some reviews and give these a try, at the price, couldn't hurt. I get EXTREMELY inaccurate readings. I've done a variety of testing different fingers and the same finger, and regardless, get highly varying results. So I end up having to use the One Touch strips anyway. The most recent results were 112-130-146, all taken within one minute. Thankfully I don't require insulin, but the medical professional in me still screams DO NOT BUY.
customer_reviews.author: Amazon Customer

customer_reviews.title: Difficult to use
customer_reviews.text: Yes. They cost less. Generally the accuracy is acceptable. However, these strips are thicker and stiffer than other test strips. The thicker the strip, the bigger the amount of blood need to get blood on the test area. I always wind up getting one or two error messages that the sample is too small before finally getting a result.
customer_reviews.author: Ron Rives

customer_reviews.title: Tested agains name brand and has lower results.
customer_reviews.text: I tested these strips against the brand name and also against a different meter brand. The other strips were comparable to each other, but the GenUltimate consistently read low, between 9-20 points lower than the others. I think they are still usable if you adjust for the potential variation in reading. I would be inclined to buy one pack of the brand-name strips to use as a control test. Every once in a while, see how the GenUltimate compares.
customer_reviews.author: jpau00

customer_reviews.title: I have using these for years, this was my first problem!
customer_reviews.text: New 50 pack opened this morning, I buy in 200 quantity. My BS usually runs around 110-130. Read 300+, I couldn't believe it, tested again...400+. Opened another 50 pack, read normally. The info on Lot/Manufacture numbers are in the photos.

customer_reviews.title: Be careful
